    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-03-10T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-03-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="284"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/1509: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Russell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-03-10T13:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 10, 1923—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 11—11:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. President Borno informed me this morning that on further consideration he
                    finds that it would be a violation of the Constitution for him to appropriate
                    the $10,000 for the preparation of internal tax law et cetera, there being no
                    law covering this subject and referred me to letter of General Receiver who in
                    the case where $1,200 <pb facs="0510" n="386" xml:id="pg_386"/> had been carried
                    in budget for commission to revise communal taxes had refused payment on the
                    ground that there was no law authorizing such commission and therefore violated
                    Constitution. President then said that funds for the necessary work desired by
                    Mr. Hord<note n="1" xml:id="d284fn1">John S. Hord, Financial Adviser of
                        Haiti.</note> could by the treaty properly be charged to 5 percent fund as
                    expenses of Financial Adviser’s office and that he authorized such a charge at
                    once.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Russell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
